@inproceedings{Cisyk2014,
abstract = {A grouting program to mitigate water inflow into a deep shaft at the Mosaic Potash Esterhazy operations was initiated based on 3D Electrical Resistivity Imaging (ERI) from the shaft and historical geological information used to characterize conditions around the shaft. In 1986, installation of a grout wall was undertaken but not completed. Historical information from shaft logs during sinking and subsequent drilling during the 1986 grout wall installation indicated that fractures intersected the shaft where water inflows were observed. The 1986 grout project used acrylamide and urethane chemical grouts to reduce shaft seepage through a concrete liner from Devonian carbonate rocks. In 2004, a two dimensional ERI investigation was completed using 48 electrodes placed on a vertical line at 2 m spacing in the concrete shaft liner. The results of this survey matched geological information and a more extensive 3D ERI survey was undertaken in 2006. The 3D ERI investigation used three vertical electrode lines equally spaced around the circumference of the shaft (120 degree separation) with 134 electrodes along each line spaced at a 1 meter interval. This investigation provided the first and only information as to the extent of success and failure of the 1986 grouting operation in a carbonate system with matrix or intercrystalline, and fracture porosity. Since the ERI imaging surrounded the shaft, it helped to discriminate between both grouted and ungrouted rock. The ERI results provided sufficient evidence to support the completion of the grout wall in 2009. To our knowledge, this is the first application of a 3D ERI investigation for underground shaft work. We will discuss the grouting programs and the ERI process and results of the 3D model which revealed a significant contrast in grout penetration and the indication of linear features interpreted as open fluid transmitting fractures.},
